Verify the HMAC **before** you decode or trust anything — that's the whole point of the signature. Compute it over the exact raw bytes the provider signed (usually the raw body, not the decoded one), compare with `crypto.timingSafeEqual`, and only then base64-decode for processing:

```js
const sig = crypto.createHmac('sha256', secret).update(req.rawBody).digest('hex');
if (!crypto.timingSafeEqual(Buffer.from(sig), Buffer.from(req.headers['x-signature']))) {
  return res.status(401).end();
}
const decoded = Buffer.from(req.rawBody.toString(), 'base64').toString('utf8');
```

Decoding before verifying lets an attacker feed you arbitrary bytes, so order matters. Use `timingSafeEqual`, not `===`, to avoid timing leaks.
